## Agree

The v5 direction is right: equal co-operators, explicit cross-validation, round contracts, and process integrity as a first-class gate all address real v4 weaknesses. v4 already had “author != verifier,” but it still centralized implementation/merge judgment in Claude Code and relied too much on convention. v5’s contract/lock layer is the correct next abstraction.

I also agree with shrinking `.claude/CLAUDE.md` and adding a Codex-facing `AGENTS.md`. The current persona file is only 102 lines, but it mixes role assignment, gates, context protocol, skills, metrics, and ambiguity policy. Moving stable process into `context_harness/operator/` is cleaner.

The design-revision workflow already expects Phase 0 capture, Phase 1 gap analysis, Phase 2 contract update, Phase 3 slicing, Phase 4 implementation, Phase 5 evaluation, Phase 6 merge/track, Phase 7 drift detection. v5 should not replace that workflow; it should become the operator governance layer that executes it.

## Disagree (mandatory ≥ 1)

I disagree with “SKILLS.md에 최소 1건 lesson 추가됨” as a hard Gate 5 blocker. Mandatory lessons create low-signal process debt. Some rounds should close with “no new durable skill; existing rules were sufficient.” The blocker should be: retro must explicitly classify whether a new SKILLS entry is warranted, and if a repeated or novel pattern was found, then SKILLS update is mandatory.

I also disagree with the strict “FILE_INDEX 경유 없이 bulk read 금지” plus “`ls <dir>` 탐색 금지” rule as written. It is directionally good, but impractical and likely to fail under real debugging. Operators sometimes need `rg --files`, `rg`, `git diff --name-only`, or focused `ls` to verify current state. The rule should ban undirected bulk-loading and require logging when opening unindexed files, not ban directory inspection outright.

A smaller but important contradiction: the proposal says `FILE_INDEX.md` has “제한 없음” in the table, then later says `FILE_INDEX.md ≤ 250줄`. Pick one. I prefer a 250-line index plus topic-specific sub-indexes if needed.

## Counter-proposals

Make `spec.md` immutable after lock creation. Amendments should not edit it in place. Use `spec.amendment.N.md` plus a `supersedes` field in the lock, or generate `spec.effective.md` from base spec + amendments. This preserves auditability.

Replace mandatory disagreement with mandatory “challenge section.” For nontrivial decisions, it must include at least one concrete disagreement, risk, or alternative rejected. For pure factual meetings, it can say “No normative decision; verified facts only,” with evidence pointers. This keeps the anti-hallucination tripwire without forcing fake dissent.

Split Gate 5 into two levels: `process-integrity-blockers` and `process-advisories`. Missing lock mapping, contract mutation, unreviewed meeting, or missing FILE_INDEX entry for new operator docs should block. Missing SKILLS update should block only when the retro identifies a new durable lesson.

Codex load should be reduced. In the current matrix, Codex owns detailed design, first-pass verification, real-use evaluation, and co-owns second-pass coding decisions. That creates latency and makes Codex the bottleneck. Move real-use evaluation to a rotating role or split it: Codex writes eval protocol, Claude Code executes runtime capture, Codex reviews the report.

## Answers to Open Questions

### Q1 Gemini purge vs tier-3

Keep Gemini as tier-3 emergency capacity, but remove it from the normal team manifest path. It should be documented as an escalation tool with explicit triggers: context window overflow, independent arbitration after Claude/Codex deadlock, or large artifact summarization where both operators agree it adds value. Do not let it participate in routine gates; that adds noise and another stale role contract.

### Q2 Meetings as markdown vs JSONL

Use markdown as the human-facing meeting artifact, backed by a small machine-readable front matter block. Pure JSONL is audit-friendly but poor for actual reasoning. Plain markdown is readable but weak for enforcement. Recommended shape:

```md
---
round: round_deepsight_r1
stage: detailed_design
status: decided
participants: [claude_code, codex]
decision_id: ...
contract_hash: ...
---
```

Important decisions should also append one JSONL event to `process-log.jsonl`, but the meeting body should remain markdown.

### Q3 Disagreement-must-be-recorded scope

Apply it to normative or design-affecting decisions, not pure fact gathering. The stronger rule should be: every decision meeting must record at least one objection, risk, rejected alternative, or explicit uncertainty. If none exists, the meeting must state why the decision is factual/mechanical and cite evidence. Fake disagreement is worse than no disagreement.

### Q4 Evaluation screenshot location

Keep raw screenshots under `context_harness/reports/<round_id>/screenshots/` and put operator summaries under `context_harness/operator/rounds/<round_id>/` or `operator/contracts/<round_id>/evaluation_manifest.md`. Screenshots are evaluation artifacts, not operator doctrine. The operator layer should point to them and record hashes/paths.

### Q5 Codex load balance

Current proposal over-concentrates Codex. Codex should own detailed design and first-pass architecture/code review. Real-use evaluation should be split or rotated. For design-heavy rounds, Codex can define the eval rubric, but Claude Code should gather runtime evidence and run the screenshot pipeline, then Codex reviews conclusions. That keeps author/verifier separation and avoids making Codex the serialized choke point.

### Q6 First-round scope (all 8 screens vs sliced)

Slice it. The existing design-revision workflow says one sprint should affect at most 1-2 screens, with theme tokens first, navigation second, screen redesigns after, and accessibility/HIG sweep last. Eight screens at once will make visual QA, contract diffs, and blocker attribution too muddy. First round should be: capture/gap/contract, token sprint, nav sprint if needed, then screen clusters.

### Q7 Sequence (v5 then deepsight, or parallel)

Do a minimal v5 bootstrap first, then deepsight through v5. Do not fully perfect v5 before product work, and do not process deepsight under v4. The bootstrap should include OPERATOR, FILE_INDEX, STAGE_CONTRACT, MEETING_PROTOCOL, lock schema, and one dry-run meeting. Then start deepsight as the first real v5 round and let the retro harden the system.

## Missing Pieces (a-g above)

(a) Linter enforcement mechanics: define a canonical `operator/lint/` or `context_harness/operator/lint_config.yaml`, plus a script such as `harness/check_operator_round.py`. The round lock stores the lint config hash. Gate 5 fails closed if the config is missing, hash mismatches, or the checker cannot run. Enforcement owner should be the cross-validator for the stage, not the performer.

(b) Contract immutability checking: lock hashes for `spec.md`, `file_whitelist.txt`, `convention_version.txt`, `lint_config.txt`, and `acceptance.md` are necessary but not sufficient. The protocol must say: after lock creation, base contract files are never edited. Changes require an amendment meeting and new amendment artifact. Any direct diff to base contract files during an active round is a hard stop.

(c) Operator-layer drift detection: add an operator audit that checks OPERATOR, FILE_INDEX, STAGE_CONTRACT, MEETING_PROTOCOL, REGULATION, PROCESS_AUDIT_CHECKLIST, and SESSION_RESUME for contradictions. Examples: role matrix mismatch, stale file paths, line-limit violations, missing new files from FILE_INDEX, and stage names diverging across docs. This should run at Gate 5 and every operator amendment.

(d) Non-convergent meetings: add a time box and escalation rule. Example: after two written counter-rounds or 24 hours without convergence, mark `status: escalated`, summarize both positions, list the reversible/default option, and ask the human for a decision. No silent compromise and no endless meeting.

(e) Parallel vs serial cross-validation: use parallel for independent evidence gathering and evaluation, serial for contract-setting and approval. Phase 1 gap analysis can be parallel with each operator producing observations, then reconciliation serial. Phase 2 contract update should be serial: one drafts, the other reviews. Implementation can be parallel only for disjoint file whitelists/worktrees. Gate 2 evaluator reviews should be parallel. Merge/round closure should be serial.

(f) Clear non-overlapping work zones: define default ownership, with crossing protocol. Codex owns design/spec drafts, acceptance criteria, eval rubrics, architecture review, and `AGENTS.md`. Claude Code owns implementation briefs, Swift code changes, runtime execution, and `.claude/CLAUDE.md`. Shared/operator docs require meeting approval. If a task crosses zones, create a meeting note, expand the whitelist, and assign performer/cross-validator before edits.

(g) Full autonomy with human approval: autonomy should run inside approved contracts. Human approval is required for product contract changes, user-visible design direction, security/privacy policy changes, release/merge decisions when blockers are unresolved, and non-convergent operator disputes. Human approval should not be required for routine sprint slicing, implementation within a locked whitelist, test fixes inside scope, or process-log/report generation. That gives the loop room to run without letting agents redefine the product silently.

## Recommendation

merge-with-changes

The proposal is a strong v5 foundation, but I would not merge it as-is because the enforcement layer is underspecified and a few rules will create process theater: mandatory SKILLS additions, forced disagreement for factual meetings, and overly strict read discipline. Add fail-closed lint/lock mechanics, immutable contract amendments, operator-doc drift checks, a deadlock escalation rule, and a clearer Codex load split. With those changes, v5 is ready to become the harness layer for the deepsight redesign.
